{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39350122-f95d-49f2-92a8-d9979c6f2164","content":"Here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root.\n- The server communicates over **stdin/stdout** (stdio transport), which is what `dotnet run` uses by default with the C# MCP SDK.\n- If your server uses environment variables, add an `\"env\"` block:\n  ```jsonc\n  \"env\": { \"MY_VAR\": \"value\" }\n  ```\n- If you've already published the server, replace `\"dotnet\", [\"run\", \"--project\", \"...\"]` with the path to the compiled executable.\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will prompt you to **start the MCP server** in the Copilot chat panel. You can also manage it via **\"MCP: List Servers\"** in the command palette.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"363a64fd-f38a-47ae-92d9-d6b0cb6f5401","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're asking for configuration guidance, not for me to create the project. Let me just provide the mcp.json configuration guidance.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"201F:229C6C:1611E96:18BF726:6A0521C2"},"id":"8203604f-d90c-41aa-b6d1-5308b93d106e","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:13:48.450Z","parentId":"3d4a8d5b-014e-4f40-b58b-06402675ef8a"}
